<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Resolve Your Skirmishes in the Right Order<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.87)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9935'>Gerald "tangent" Tan</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9935&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 23, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Have you ever wanted to kick yourself because you resolved skirmishes in the wrong order? Well, hopefully this article will help you resolve them all in the right order next time. We will first look at a few general tips in resolving and looking at each shadow culture in turn to see what kind of surprises each of them can turn up so we can be prepared against them and help us resolve in the right order.<br>
<br>
The first most obvious thing people look for are minions which adds strength whenever there are other minions around, e.g. Ancient Chieftain, Witchking, Morgul Warden, etc. If you are able to kill other minions to weaken this minion, make sure you kill the others off first. This should be a no-brainer.<br>
<br>
The second thing to consider what power-ups your opponents may be playing and tempt him to play them at the wrong time. Here&#39;s an example. You Frodo, Gandalf with Staff, Boromir facing 3 Nazguls. You have a stealth in your hand, and he has a blade tip and 2 black breaths in his support area. How do you resolve? Obviously you cannot resolve Boromir last because he will surely take the blade tip. If you resolve Boromir first, the shadow player may be tempted to save the blade tip for Frodo or Gandalf, who will of course both cancel the skirmishes. If he isn&#39;t tempted to save the blade tip, you lose nothing. In the same way, it is probably better to resolve losing skirmishes first (opponents may be holding on to Enheartened Foe or similar cards and tempted to save it for another campanion),<br>
<br>
With a few Saruman&#39;s Ambitions/Long Dark in play, you can also use the same principles if you are able to save only one of two campanions with a card in your hand and he has to guess which minion to pump with Sarumon&#39;s Ambition. This becomes more or less a guessing and a game of bluff, but against less experienced, it may be best to simply resolve the skirmish first where you want him to waste the powerups. Perhaps the less experienced players will be more easily tempted to use the powerups at first oppourtunity. This of course holds true if you anticipate other powerups hidden (or have seen them revealed) in the shadow player&#39;s hand (Bred for Battle, Drums in the Deep, Enduring Evil, Dark Whispers etc).<br>
<br>
Playing against a Moria Culture:<br>
<br>
Plundered Armories is one thing most people forget about. This allows the shadow player to transfer a Moria weapon from a dying minion to another minion (spears and scimitars for free, moria axe for 1). You want to limit this kind of transfers if possible, especially with scimitars and/or goblin armories in play, allowing the shadow player to draw an extra card (usually won&#39;t be able to play it, but it might help in reconciling the hand) or add twilight to the pool, not to mention beefing up the other minions. You therefore want to resolve the skirmishes against minions which do not have weapons before the minions which have weapons, so when the minions with weapons die, they have no one to transfer the weapons too.<br>
<br>
Goblin Swarms. If you intend to run, you want to resolve in a way which tempts him to put his winning minions on the swarms. If you don&#39;t intend to run, you want to resolve in a way which makes him leave his minions in play. Does resolving the winning minions first or last make the shadow player more or less likely to stack the minion? I don&#39;t quite have an idea at the moment.<br>
<br>
Guard Commander. If there&#39;s twilight left in the pool, you want to kill him first to the shadow player guess which minions to powerup before he dies. <br>
<br>
Relentless. Beware of this card. If you intend to stealth, resolve all other skrimishes first so that he is less likely to have 3 orcs to spot.<br>
<br>
<br>
Against Isengaard shadow<br>
<br>
Uruk Slayer. Skirmish him first before you resolve other skirmishes where you will be using powerups which adds twilight.<br>
<br>
Uruk Spy. If your Ring-bearer is likely to put on the One Ring in his skirmish, make sure you kill the Uruk Spy first.<br>
<br>
Wariness. See Relentless. If you intend to stealth, you may need to kill off all other uruks first.<br>
<br>
<br>
Against Ringwraith culture<br>
<br>
In the Ringwraith&#39;s Wake, Threshold of Shadow, Dark Whispers, All Veils Remove, The Twilight World, Wraith World. With this cards, it is usually best to resolve the Ring-bearer last. Let all the other skirmishes resolve first before the Ring-bearer has to put on the ring or take the burdens. However....<br>
<br>
Return to Its Master. Seldom played, and even if it is used, often there&#39;s not much you can do. If the Ring-bearer can survive the two skirmishes, you would probably prefer to resolve him first (so the other campanions don&#39;t skirmish). <br>
<br>
Drawn to its Power. Resolve the dying campanion last, of course.<br>
<br>
<br>
And finally Sauron.<br>
<br>
Gleaming Spires Will Crumle, Orc Banner. Resolve all winning skirmish first, of course. <br>
<br>
Seeking It Always. Kill all trackers first if you intend to stealth.<br>
<br>
Tower Lieutenant. Resolve this guy last, especially if you intend to play powerups from your hand which may get discarded first if you resolve him early.<br>
<br>
Southern Spies. Resolve the Ring-bearer last.<br>
<br>
<br>
Summary.<br>
<br>
In general, you want to skirmish Guard Commanders, Uruk Spies and Uruk Slayers first. Then resolve losing skirmishes, winning skirmishes next, followed by skirmish with the Ring bearer, and stealth skirmishes last. <br>
<br>
But if you are able to see the shadow player&#39;s hand and spot certain conditions in play (Gleaming Spires, Orc Banner), make sure you resolve accordingly.<br>
